@NODE "Introduction" "Introduction"
@TOC "MAIN"

MarkIt is a simple shell-based program for adding new URLs and their
descriptions to your bookmark files. At the moment it only supports HTML
bookmark files (which I use), however these are compatible with any browser out
there. I personally put all my bookmarks into HTML lists since I use several
browsers on various platforms, so storing them in the format of any particular
browser is quite worthless for me.

I started this program to simply make it easier and faster to add bookmarks to
my own files, however I've decided to expand it a little by adding
configuration options etc. as a C-programming learning experience - there
wasn't really anything out there that suited my needs (of being a compulsive
URL collector :), so I figured I'd learn C and write something useful as I went
along.

MarkIt will prompt you to enter the HTML file you wish to add a new URL to,
from a pre-defined list in the config file. You then enter the URL and
description, and the program will do the rest.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Installation" "Installation"
@TOC "MAIN"
Installation:
Copy MarkIt to anywhere in your path
Create config file, "ENVARC:MarkIt.cfg" (See Config: for instructions)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Configuration" "Configuration"
@TOC "MAIN"
Config:
The config file is a simple ASCII file, with the first line consisting on the
number of columns per line in your console window (usually 80+), and each other
line consisting of two options: the location of an HTML bookmark file, and a short description of this
file.
e.g:

80
SYS:Drawer/Amiga.html Amiga hotlinks
SYS:Drawer/Search.html Search engines
SYS:Drawer/Homepages.html Friends' Homepages

The filename must not contain any spaces. I suggest you try and keep the
description as short as possible - that way the program will display multiple
columns of your bookmark files, which is generally a bit faster and (I think)
easer to read.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage" "Usage"
@TOC "MAIN"
Usage:
Simply enter "MarkIt" in the shell. MarkIt will then present you with a
numbered list of your bookmark files, and request you to enter the
corresponding number for that bookmark file.
e.g

"0: Amiga hotlinks    1: Search engines    2: Friends' Homepages

Enter number:"

To add a URL to your Homepages bookmark file, you would enter "2". MarkIt will
then ask you for the URL of the homepage you want to add, e.g
www.mypages.com/~bob_home/
You will then be asked to enter a description for this URL, e.g "Bob".

Simply hit return at any point to exit.

MarkIt will then add the line:
<A><HREF="http://www.mypages.com/~bob_home/>Bob</A>
to your Homepages.html bookmark file.

It's all rather simple :) It's not the best-looking way of doing it, however
it's fast/simple, which helps when adding a whole list of new URLs :)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Future" "Future"
@TOC "MAIN"
Future:

-Hopefully figure out a way of determining the column/line width of the console
 window, so users don't have to figure it out and put it in the config file
 themselves.

-Add the option to add multiple URLs, without having to re-run the program
 (Already written, just needs to be cleaned up before adding)
*Done. But should it assume the user wants to add every URL to the same
 bookmark file, or reprint the list and ask for a new bookmark file selection?
 Should this be different if a non-listed bookmark file is selected via the
 requester?

-Clean up the bookmark file list output, and possibly make output faster
*Done. Need to determine how wide the shell window is, for people without shell
 windows the same size as mine (91) - set to 80 columns for releases.

-Whatever people ask for :)

-Bookmark file selection is a bit old-fashioned, although I don't mind it
 myself. Perhaps a simple GUI may be the way to go... once I figure out how :)

-Add command line args to give the option of choosing between 2 config files:
 a small, short and quick one for commonly-used bookmark files, or a long, slow
 and large one for all bookmark files.

-Add some error checking :)

-Perhaps add a prefs file editor - although I doubt anyone would use the
 program that much to find it useful, or would have problems with making their
 own prefs file.

@ENDNODE

